<article id="node-16963">
<h1 >3.4.8.80 RAFS - Farmer Retains an Interest in the Home</h1>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> THIS SCHEME CLOSED on 31 July 2001 and the following INFORMATION is FOR HISTORICAL PURPOSES ONLY.</p>
<h2>Effect on farm (<a href="../../../1/1/f/100">1.1.F.100</a>) value</h2>
<p>If the farmer retains a life, freehold or leasehold interest in the home, the value is excluded from the calculation of the value of the farm and assets, as long as the area of land retained does NOT exceed 2 hectares. This also applies if the applicant excises the house and curtilage from the remainder of the farm to retain ownership of that portion.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Excision will only apply where local zoning laws permit it.</p>
</div>
<p>A short-term lease or rental agreement does NOT satisfy this provision. In this case, the house and curtilage would be INCLUDED in the value of the farm and farm assets.</p>
<p>The following table explains how the farmer's interest in the house should be confirmed:</p>
<table><thead><tr><th scope="col">If the interest is…</th>
<th scope="col">Then…</th>
</tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>a life interest,</td>
<td>there is no legal requirement for the interest to be documented.
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Applicants with a life interest would be advised to protect their interest by obtaining a written agreement, although there is no legal requirement for them to do so.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr><tr><td>freehold,</td>
<td>a copy of the certificate of title should be sought.</td>
</tr><tr><td>leasehold,</td>
<td>a copy of the written leasehold agreement between the eligible descendant and the farmer should be sought.
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> This would apply to properties subject to a pastoral or other long term transferable leasehold arrangement.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr></tbody></table><h2>Effect on farmer when they retain an interest in the home</h2>
<p>A farmer who retains an interest in the home is treated as a homeowner (<a href="../../../1/1/h/75">1.1.H.75</a>), and the value of the house and curtilage are exempt when calculating their assets. The following table explains the treatment in other situations:</p>
<table><thead><tr><th scope="col">If the farmer…</th>
<th scope="col">Then…</th>
</tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>later vacates the house,</td>
<td>the value of the life interest will be included as an asset, subject to the usual rules on temporary vacations or vacation to enter a nursing home (<a href="../../../1/1/n/140">1.1.N.140</a>).</td>
</tr><tr><td>relinquishes the life interest,</td>
<td>the deprivation provisions will apply.</td>
</tr></tbody></table><p>A life interest under <a href="../../../acronyms#rafs" title="Retirement assistance for farmers scheme">RAFS</a> is NOT a granny flat right.</p>
<p><strong>Exception:</strong> Different provisions apply if the farm was legally transferred before 15 September 1997, and the farmer retained only a right to reside in the farmhouse. In this case, an amount equal to the market value of the house and curtilage should still be deducted from the net value of the property.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Previously, a life interest WAS treated as a granny flat right. Any amount previously assessed, as the value of the granny flat right is not relevant to the RAFS assessment.</p>
</div>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> In August 1994, a farmer gifted his farm worth $200,000, including a dwelling on the property valued at $45,000, and also claimed Age. The farmer retained a right to reside in the farmhouse, which was given a value of $100,000 under the granny flat 'reasonableness test'. In relation to this gift, $90,000 is currently assessed as a deprived asset. If this farmer were to apply under RAFS to have this deprived asset disregarded, the net value of the farm would be $155,000 - that is, the value of the total property less the market value of the home at the time of transfer.</p>
</div>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section 12A(2) A person has a granny flat interest…</p>
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="../../../4/1">4.1</a> Deprivation of Income &amp; Assets, <a href="../../../4/6/3">4.6.3</a> Assessing the Principal Home, <a href="../../../4/6/4">4.6.4</a> Assessing Special Residences &amp; Aged Accommodation</p>
</div>
</article>	<div id="view-last-reviewed-date">
		
		  
